Credit Card Customer Segmentation using K-Means Clustering

📌 Project Overview

Customer segmentation enables financial institutions to better understand customer behavior, optimize credit offerings, and deliver personalized marketing strategies. By grouping customers with similar financial characteristics, banks can identify high-value customers, detect underserved segments, and improve credit portfolio management.

This project develops a Credit Card Customer Segmentation model using the K-Means Clustering algorithm. Customers are grouped based on Income Category, Gender, and Credit Limit to generate actionable business insights for targeted marketing, credit limit optimization, and premium product recommendations.

The project demonstrates an end-to-end unsupervised machine learning workflow, including data preprocessing, feature scaling, clustering, visualization, and business interpretation.

🎯 Business Objectives
Segment customers into distinct groups based on financial characteristics.
Identify high-value customers eligible for premium credit products.
Detect underserved customers with high income but relatively low credit limits.
Support personalized marketing and customer retention strategies.
Enable data-driven credit line management.

📊 Dataset
Dataset: Credit Card Customer Dataset
Features Used
Gender
Income Category
Credit Limit

Additional customer attributes are available in the dataset but were not used in the clustering model.

🛠️ Technologies Used
Python
Pandas
NumPy
Scikit-learn
Matplotlib
📈 Data Preparation

The dataset was prepared before clustering through several preprocessing steps.

Data Cleaning
Removed unnecessary whitespace from categorical variables.
Checked for missing values.
Removed records with missing values in key clustering features.
Feature Encoding

Categorical variables were converted into ordinal numerical values.
Gender Encoding
Gender	Value
Female	1
Male	2
Income Category Encoding
Income Category	Value
Less than $40K	1
$40K – $60K	2
$60K – $80K	3
$80K – $120K	4
$120K+	5
Unknown	6

⚙️ Feature Scaling
Since K-Means is distance-based, all selected features were normalized using MinMaxScaler.

Scaled Features:
Gender
Income Category
Credit Limit

This ensures that no single feature dominates the clustering process.

🤖 Customer Segmentation using K-Means
An unsupervised machine learning model was built using the K-Means Clustering algorithm.
Model Configuration
Algorithm: K-Means
Number of Clusters: 5
Random State: 42

Each customer was assigned to one of five customer segments.

📊 Segment Profiling
After clustering, business-oriented segment profiles were generated.
For each segment, the following KPIs were calculated:
Number of customers
Average income level
Average credit limit
Average gender distribution

Segments were ranked according to average credit limit to distinguish high-value customer groups.

💼 Business Insights
The analysis identified two key customer groups:

⭐ High-Value Segments
Customer groups with average credit limits above the overall portfolio average.
Potential actions:
Premium credit cards
Exclusive rewards
Wealth management offers
Loyalty programs

📈 Under-Served Segments
Customers with:
High income
Below-average credit limits

Potential actions:

Credit limit increase
Personalized financial products
Upselling premium services
Targeted retention campaigns

📊 Visualizations
The project includes multiple visualizations to interpret customer segments.
Customer Distribution
Number of customers in each cluster
Average Credit Limit by Segment
Comparison of average credit limits across clusters
3D Customer Segmentation

Interactive-style 3D scatter plot illustrating customer groups using:

Gender
